(203, 59, '___________ responsibility is a regulatory framework that holds waste generators responsible for their hazardous waste from the moment it is created (\"cradle\") until its final disposal or reuse (\"grave\")', 'Cradle-to grave', 1, '2026-03-09 06:47:37'),
(204, 59, 'Fugitive emissions are unintended releases of gas from equipment such as valves, seals, and  ____________', 'Pipelines', 1, '2026-03-09 06:48:43'),
(205, 62, 'Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) is guided by the global blueprint known as the (1) ____________________, which outlines four Priorities for Action. Central to understanding disaster risk is the Disaster Risk Equation: Risk = (Hazard Ã— (2) ____________________) / (3) ____________________. This equation demonstrates that risk can be reduced by either decreasing vulnerability or increasing community strengths. The (4) ____________________ model, developed by Wisner et al., illustrates how disasters occur when the progression of vulnerability meets a hazard event. Vulnerability itself is multidimensional, including physical, economic, social, and (5) ____________________ dimensions. In Nigeria, agencies such as (6) ____________________ coordinate national response, while at the state level, (7) ____________________ handle local coordination. The (8) ____________________ Framework emphasizes the principle of \"Build Back Better\" in recovery. Climate change acts as a risk (9) ____________________, exacerbating existing hazards. DRR is therefore recognized as the first line of (10) ____________________ to climate change.', 'Sendai Framework\n\nVulnerability\n\nCapacity\n\nPressure and Release (PAR)\n\nAttitudinal\n\nNEMA (National Emergency Management Agency)\n\nSEMA (State Emergency Management Agency)\n\nSendai\n\nMultiplier\n\nAdaptation', 10, '2026-03-09 13:09:19'),
(206, 62, 'Nigeria faces a multi-hazard environment requiring comprehensive risk assessment. In the Niger Delta, (1) ____________________ spills represent a major technological hazard, while in Northern Nigeria, (2) ____________________ is a slow-onset environmental disaster affecting livelihoods. The 2022 floods that affected 34 states demonstrated the importance of effective (3) ____________________ mechanisms among NEMA, SEMA, and humanitarian actors. The (4) ____________________ system, used in humanitarian response, organizes sectors such as Shelter, Protection, and WASH to prevent duplication and gaps. In Lokoja, early warning systems failed partly because warnings did not translate into (5) ____________________ action, highlighting the need for (6) ____________________-centered early warning. Community-Based Disaster Risk Management (CBDRM) emphasizes that communities should be active (7) ____________________ in DRR, not passive beneficiaries. A key CBDRM tool is the participatory (8) ____________________ and Capacity Assessment (VCA), which maps both risks and local strengths such as kinship networks, market associations, and (9) ____________________ knowledge. Social workers play a critical role in facilitating these processes and ensuring marginalized groups, including women and children, have voice and (10) ____________________ in decision-making.', 'Oil\n\nDesertification\n\nCoordination\n\nCluster\n\nEarly\n\nPeople/Community\n\nParticipants/Partners\n\nVulnerability\n\nIndigenous/Local/Traditional\n\nParticipation/Representation', 10, '2026-03-09 13:10:10'),
(207, 62, 'Climate change acts as a risk multiplier, as demonstrated by the (1) ____________________ Basin crisis, where the lake has shrunk by over 90% since the 1960s. This environmental change has destroyed fishing and farming livelihoods, intensified competition for resources, and contributed to (2) ____________________ in the region. Such slow-onset disasters interact with existing social vulnerabilities, creating cascading risks. Disasters do not affect everyone equally; they amplify existing inequalities. In Borno\'s IDP camps, women face specific (3) ____________________ risks, including gender-based violence during daily activities like firewood collection. Children, especially girls, are at increased risk of (4) ____________________ marriage as families adopt negative coping strategies under economic stress. A (5) ____________________ analysis is therefore essential for understanding who is at risk and why. The (6) ____________________ Framework\'s Priority 1 calls for understanding disaster risk in all its dimensions, including social and gendered factors. Social workers must advocate for women\'s (7) ____________________ in camp governance committees, not just protection as beneficiaries. This requires designing interventions that address root causes, such as livelihood programs that target (8) ____________________ and ensure access to resources. The principle of (9) ____________________ in humanitarian action means ensuring interventions do not reinforce stereotypes or create dependency. Ultimately, building community (10) ____________________ requires addressing both environmental hazards and the social structures that create differential vulnerability.', 'Lake Chad\n\nConflict/Insurgency/Instability\n\nProtection/Security\n\nEarly/Child\n\nGender\n\nSendai\n\nParticipation/Representation/Inclusion\n\nWomen\n\nDo No Harm\n\nResilience', 10, '2026-03-09 13:10:52'),
(208, 60, '___________ is an example of government agencies in Nigeria for managing environmental hazards', 'Federal Environmental Protection Agency', 1, '2026-03-09 13:33:07'),
(209, 60, 'Four examples of biological factors in the environment are', 'Bacteria, Fungi, Viruses, Algae, Pollens, Protozoa', 4, '2026-03-09 14:04:08'),
(210, 60, 'Three protozoan diseases that can be transmitted through water and the respective causative agents areâ€¦..', 'Trypanosomiasâ€¦..Trypanosoma brucei\n Schistosomiasis caused by Schistosoma sp\n Malaria caused by Plasmodium falciparum', 6, '2026-03-09 14:15:11'),
